At the end of the trade, the Prague Stock Exchange flipped into the negative
After the fall on Tuesday morning, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily exchanges.
On Tuesday, from the start of the trade, the Prague Stock Exchange resumed its fall the day before, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in shares on Wall Street.
The reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the stabilization plan for the US financial sector, is noticeable here too.
Fall of stock in Asia
Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic drop on Tuesday, even though the indicators managed to clear some of the losses during the day.
The Hang Seng index of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost four percent during the exchanges, but later it erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, following the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, lost 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but ultimately managed to reduce the losses to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
“The hesitation about the U.S. bailout will affect financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are the same as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. lawmakers should soon resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there would be a risk that other countries would be affected.
The Bloodbath of American Actions
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the project to support the financial system, to which it should have devoted up to 700 billion dollars (nearly 12 trillion K<0xC4><0x8D>).
Legislators thus denied the call for support for President George Bush's project.
According to Bush, the project should address the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indices experienced the biggest drop in the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones index lost nearly seven percent, having experienced a drop of such magnitude for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress cedes: U.S. government can inject $700 billion into banks
The leaders of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to the vote early next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a decisive turning point in the talks on the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of financial assistance of $700 billion (about 12 trillion crowns), granted to the U.S. financial system.
Success is not certain.
Indeed, before they can publish the final version of the law and put it to the vote, Congressmen must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be discussed Monday in the House of Representatives.
Barney Frank, the chairman of the House’s banking and financial regulation committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be put to the vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be adopted should be a major psychological factor in reviving the financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms through which market aid can be effective, there will be a "disillusionment".
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made great progress.
We have settled our divergent views on the shape of the market stabilization package," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be held as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, in order to give the bottom of the government a final form.
It should buy back from financial corporations the unsellable real estate assets that lead financial corporations to considerable losses and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We still need to continue this market recovery plan, but I think we’re in it,” Paulson said.
A signal for Asian exchanges
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on falling stock markets.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are making sure that Congress reaches a final deal as early as Sunday.
They want to calm investors before trading begins in the Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the congressional decision could affect Monday’s trades.
At the moment, it is impossible to say with certainty when the two Houses of Congress will proceed to the vote, or whether the negotiations will not be blocked at the last moment by this or that problem.
Legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, the law will continue to undergo many changes.
The total amount allocated to the system must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, should be made available as soon as possible.
But if Congress feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the option of blocking the allocation of the remaining amount, following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, then, finally, $350 billion.
Mr. Bush welcomed the progress in the negotiations
Although the president can veto this decision, Congress has the option of putting it in the minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain funding for the purchase of bad real estate securities, the value of which fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
“All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to proceed to the vote on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
U.S. President George W. Bush is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, said lawmakers agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, the protection of contributors from losses, the settlement agreement, and the timeline of the plan.
The new law also provides for the limitation of these golden parachutes for the directors of the companies participating in the program and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on this issue and have made significant progress towards an agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also provides assistance for homeowners, who have problems paying for it.
The government should negotiate new deposits in the case of mortgages it will buy, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to the chief economist of Patria Finance David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
"And this is due to the fact that we do not know what the mechanism and the price of the buyback of the troubled assets will be.
This point will be decisive for deciding on the share of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek told iHNed.cz.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or at the beginning of next week, is not, according to Marek, as important as this.
"It is much more important that Congressmen agree, as of this week, that they support this plan and that they will dedicate it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, matters most at the moment," Marek said.
A push to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobile phones know how to play MP3 files, no MP3 player knows how to phone.
As a result, it seems clear that it is better to buy only one phone.
However, there are sufficient reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house an expensive high-end gramophone to put the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl record, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason, for this to happen.
Now, if there are stacked vinyl records in your shelves, with art rock, jazz or blues, you are at least likely dreaming of such a gramophone.
The same goes for music on the go, that is, compressed music, to put it simplified - music in MP3.
There are also categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan would struggle to support headphones bought for twenty crowns on the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The battery life is also crucial.
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are unknown features, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, phone calls and SMS sending, it is able to play music and movies, to record them, it has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, even be used for navigation.
And if you take smartphones and communicators into account, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator knows how to grill meat and no TV will take pictures, we are practically witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without drawbacks.
The larger the number of functions you use, the shorter the interval between two reloads.
And playing music is one of the most important energy goinfres.
There are few mobile devices that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this regard, music players (especially the most rudimentary ones) are significantly better performers.
In the case of cheap mobile phones, count that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get yourself, to be sure, a second recharge for work - this being true even for more expensive devices.
This problem will not arise for MP3 players, which are capable, as a result of recharging, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing ones.
Another problem occurs when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, that a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
Music can, of course, be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers are able to do so without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in the mobiles.
As for the drives, you do not need, except (iPod), any software.
Just fill in, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will create a media library themselves, sorted by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or by the user's judgment.
Some devices display only one index with a tree structure, like the Windows Explorer, while others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with an operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
In choosing a concrete device, you are especially interested in the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of ordering.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you are going to listen to it only for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading the MP3s.
Virtually all mobile devices are now capable of this.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to play.
All manage to play MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have exactly this format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also play music in WMA format.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Simply visit the corresponding web pages of the operator (or those of another provider) from the mobile phone and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to get a musical mobile.
The supply of operators is unfortunately miserable and it is, in most cases, limited to radio tubes quickly made.
The prices are not the lowest either.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people still wear their mobiles on themselves.
Every time you want to listen to something, all you have to do is get the phone out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have on you headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in speakers, which almost all mobiles have, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of music mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three or four thousand crowns, you can have a walkman already very suitable.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the absence of an output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and better equipped, also equipped with an entrance for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Really anyone manages to control the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the command to that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones get away with even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or a iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, choose specialized walkman phones (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and this is how the convenience of the control is closer to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles in the walkman series have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that has gone the farthest in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a longer battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours) is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
- Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we are still missing something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the last steps of the European Commission in the field of the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has repeatedly stated that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic, choruses with the operators.
It is probably true that a classical operator with its own network apparently no longer has much luck (by the way, now it would hardly find frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable drop in prices, to which, subsequently, the traditional operators also had to react.
Yet, even before party troubles such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, voices similar to those we hear today were heard in Britain.
However, it turned out that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator has managed to gain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let’s add that behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns, among other things, the U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be efficient, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high construction, operation and maintenance costs of the mobile network.
This is how in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least twice as cheap as its competitors.
However, as Mobilking’s example in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity shot.
In fact, this operator specifically targets men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work in our country as well.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>, the spokesman for Vodafone, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most of the virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, a spokesman for the financial group Penta, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do their best so that a potential competitor can not appear.
The GTS Novera Group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of corporate customers, has not for a long time concealed its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already negotiated this possibility several times with all the Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations," said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So the future may be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we may be able to host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
“Right now, we don’t believe there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is very specific compared to others.
At the moment, no topic with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 press department said in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> said in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
“It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate in such a limited time frame, we should have a concrete agreement right now.”
Instead, Vodafone focuses on fulfilling requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared fees and infrastructure.
This, in our opinion, means the most contributions from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities: in step with the operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore a decrease in their profit.
So what good is it to facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to get along like fairgrounds. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The biggest apparent pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, when the U:fon was created, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> web pages.
However, today, U:fon can be used as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> noted in this regard: "Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the market entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and especially his services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, this is not only about the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
“The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, because the offer of potential interested parties has not a priori presented enough interest for conventional operators," Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS clarified in response to our question.
Such a statement would not be surprising on the part of the representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Especially since Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the prices of mobile phone services."
However, pressing for fair market functioning and lower prices is apparently not in the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question, whether this is really a coincidence, arises naturally.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to chance and the fierce fight of the competition.
"The Office has not identified any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore none has a corresponding increased responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even from the telecommunications regulator," Chaloupa said in a statement.
One of the many points of disagreement is the interpretation of the dominant position in the market.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained each time.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
Thus, it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators are visibly proceeding in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Taking back responsibility for the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common turn in communications, through which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent amendment of the Telecommunications Act to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications has not succeeded, although many experts have promised an improvement.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know this very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one is watching, it can work.
That said, the operation of some sort of pseudo-virtual operators, many in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own mobile phone service price lists, but the latter are only partly public.
In most cases, it is about companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer customized mobile phone services.
The price lists of these firms generally reach only elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company makes in front of the operator figure of a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special (and other) price offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
“If this were to happen, it could be a violation of the contractual terms that we would consider and that could lead to a termination of the collaboration with the company in question,” said Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1>.
Nevertheless, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such an activity has not reached the heads of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, opposes such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them significant profits, and, at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators.
This is exactly what should seem strange to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another question arises at <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively broad powers to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual terms prohibit it.
When We Are No Longer the Most Expensive Country
As we have already mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a considerable decrease in the price of services.
However, in almost all countries where virtual operators appeared, the classical operators tried, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies intervened in the developed countries, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and informal pressure, they eventually obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators treat this issue in the manner of a hot potato, which is removed by passing it on to a nearby target.
As a result of the experience we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than beneficial in these cases.
But let's not throw the sleeve after the knock.
If the behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear in our house, the Czech mobile market may be on the move again.
If one of the operators has agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS can hardly remain impassive in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we will stop calling more expensively than in the rest of Europe.
