Sudeten demanded a referendum in the United States
The Sudeten Germans demanded that <0xC5><0xA0>umava be integrated into the United States in 1945.
This is the result of a letter deposited in the collections of the Jiho<0xC4><0x8D>esk<0xC3><0xA1> scient<0xC3><0xAD>eck<0xC3><0xA1> knihovna (The Scientific Library of Southern Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some Sudeten German groups allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This stems, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jiho<0xC4><0x8D>esk<0xC3><0xA1> s<0xC4><0x9B>dieck<0xC3><0xA1> knihovna.
Germans from <0xC4><0x8C>esk<0xC3><0xBD> Krumlov in the letter asked the American president not to allow "<0xC5><0xA0>umavsk<0xC3><0xA1> <0xC5><0xBE>upa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and we want to be really sure that the words proclaim that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," reads the letter, signed "Persons, to whom the fate of the <0xC5><0xA0>umava is dear".
Given that the connection to Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, ruthless attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter now ask the American president to take into his hands the protectorate for the <0xC5><0xA0>umava.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a state foreign to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which has in no way contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants," the letter reads.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the US president doubted the opinion of the Germans of <0xC5><0xA0>umava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the US, or live under the patronage of the US.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat na<0xC3><0xAF>ve, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Sudeten Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans had at least to see that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some expected that the United States and Britain would gain a certain type of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
Others believed that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in <0xC4><0x8C>eské Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German from <0xC4><0x8C>eské Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When, at the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp of the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him for him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that once they got home, the Czech would be profitable for them," Chalupa said.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, following the Bene<0xC5><0xA1> Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
You don't think - you pay!
An emotional campaign will attack the drivers
The most expensive road safety action in Czech history.
A way to characterize the emotional media campaign that intends to launch, on Wednesday, the Ministry of Transport.
