Olmert would return almost all occupied territories in exchange for peace
Ehud Olmert, the president of the Israeli interim government, spoke out in favor of the restitution of virtually all the territories occupied in 1967, including the West Bank, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
He made this statement in an interview published Monday by the daily Yedioth Ahronoth.
“We have to come to an agreement with the Palestinians, which means that it will be necessary to return almost all the (occupied) territories, or even all of them,” Olmert said.
“We will keep a certain percentage of the territory, but we will have to cede to the Palestinians an analogous percentage (of the Israeli territory), because without it, peace will not be made,” he added.
He admits that the possible restitution would include East Jerusalem.
"He who wants security in Jerusalem, and above all does not want tractors and bulldozers to crush his feet, as happened to one of my best friends, will have to give up parts of Jerusalem," said Olmert, referring to the two attacks in the city in July.
According to the prime minister, it will be necessary to find "a special solution for the Temple Mount, the sacred and historical places" located inside the Old City.
“Anyone who wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will be forced to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
It won't work," he later said.
Golan Heights Retreat
Olmert also spoke in favour of Israel's withdrawal from the Golan Heights, which he believes is an indispensable condition for the conclusion of a peace agreement with Syria.
However, this would also require some effort on the part of Damascus.
"I am not proposing to conclude peace with Syria solely on the basis of a Golan Heights retreat," he said.
“The Syrians know very well what they will have to give up in order to get the Golan.
They will have to renounce their current relations with Iran; they will have to renounce their relationship with Hezbollah (Shiite movement); they will have to renounce the constant support they give to the terrorism of Hamas (Shiite movement), of Al-Qaeda (Prime Minister), as well as of Iraq (the jihadist network).
Questions that arise after the accident: Are the stewards in the car illegal?
The law ignores them; walking in a long distance car is forbidden
In the context of the tragic accident of the Student Agency bus near Padua, Italy, the question arises whether the stewards and passengers can move inside the bus during the trip.
"If we want to comply with the law strictly and formally, the activity of a steward is contrary to the law on road traffic," said transport ministry spokesman Karel Hanzelka.
The accident in question, during which a 22-year-old hostess died, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck that crossed the road of the bus.
The girl was sitting next to the driver, on the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she had two other seats at her disposal.
However, the bus can have an accident, or even brake abruptly, even when the steward serves the coffee or distributes the newspapers.
What matters is whether the bus is under its technical data sheet equipped with standing seats or not.
If this standing seating equipment is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
The long-distance Student Agency buses have no standing seats; this has been confirmed in Aktualj.cz by the director of the company Radim Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura.
"This is an issue that we have dealt with with the ministry and, at first, it prohibits any movement of passengers.
Then they canceled it and we got passengers to go to the toilet during the trip provided they have their own seat," he said.
The law ignores the steward.
"There is no unequivocal legal interpretation of the role of steward - no legal prescription deals with that role.
On the other hand, no legal requirement prohibits the carrier from offering services.
The law on road transport only knows the term vehicle receiver; it does not define its rights and duties," Hanzelka added with more ambiguity.
Josef Pokorn<0xC3><0xBD>, the director of the Department of Road Vehicle Traffic, believes, on the contrary, that the law sufficiently addresses the problem.
“It all depends on whether the bus is allowed to offer standing seats in its approval.
It's all in there," he said.
Buses are divided into urban, where there are standing places and a limited maximum speed, intercity with standing places and a higher permitted speed, and long-distance buses without standing places with the highest permitted maximum speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
Like on a plane, says an expert.
Jaroslav Hor<0xC3><0xAD>n, expert at BESIP (road traffic safety) in transport safety, does not see the movement of stewards on board as a major problem.
"In regular traffic, there is no danger. The situation can be compared to that of service in aircraft.
Nor is it certain when turbulence will occur and the air hostess may hit her head."
"But in the event that the bus braked abruptly, the laws of physics would obviously be valid.
The same way as in a city bus or tram.
The carrier must manage the safety of stewards through internal regulations," he said, adding that from the point of view of the law, the issue is not resolved.
Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura is ready to remove these services
Student Agency is the only bus carrier to offer the services of stewards.
He hires two hundred.
Even after this accident, the director does not consider their trade as a risky trade.
"Nevertheless, as soon as I get the impression that this is a risky trade, I will remove it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and logbook at boarding.
This would also reduce costs," he said.
The safety concern is the reason given by the absence of stewards in his vehicles the director of the Asiana Alexei Litvine, which ensures, in comparison with SA, a very small number of lines.
"We don't have hostesses, we've been opposed to them since the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end in a fatal accident," he told T<0xC3><0xBD>den.cz a year ago.
A huge tragedy has happened
A young hostess from the Plze<0xC5><0x88> region, who has been working for the company for two years, died in the crash on the Naples line.
A Slovenian truck probably left the emergency stop strip without using a flashing light and blocked the way to the bus.
The driver of the latter tried to avoid it by means of a sudden maneuver, but he slipped it by his right side.
Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura refuses that the two seats reserved for the rest of the stewards have been sold.
"In the case of long-distance lines, it is not possible to reserve these seats, they are blocked."
The company plans to file a complaint against the truck driver.
For the compensation of the girl's family, the agency will not wait for the judgment of the court, but in terms of financial compensation, it also counts on the culprit.
An amendment to the law?
Not in sight
An amendment to the law, which has been in the works for more than a year, by a group of thirty experts from the Ministry of Transport, could provide details about the movements of stewards on board the bus.
"But it has not reached any conclusion on this point.
In fact, she is not too interested in buses, but rather in the points system, the maximum speed on the highway and the use of the mobile phone at the wheel," says expert Ho<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD>n.
"The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activity of the stewards as something that would fundamentally endanger the safety of passengers," Hanzelka concluded, noting that the control of the safety of buses is under the authority of the police and the office for occupational safety.
The hopes of the Düsseldorfers rest on Frankfurt.
The key words were not lacking in the letter sent by the WestLB Steering Committee to the employees of the house.
By a union of the entities of the Düsseldorf financial institution with the Frankfurt Deka-Bank, "the central financial market institution of the Sparkasse financial group" could be constituted, according to the letter released Monday.
The WestLB would provide a "competence block" doubled with sustainable productivity in such a case.
All in all, such a relationship could be the decisive impetus for other concentrations in the Landesbank sector.
This is what it looks like when a board of directors wants to demonstrate its ability to act in difficult times.
Because the WestLB, injured, is still under strong pressure.
Not only the European Commission, but also the Federal Financial Services Supervisory Authority has, only recently, made it clear to the Government of the Land of North Rhine-Westphalia that time was running out in the search for a future solution.
However, for some time now there has been a question - also on the Frankfurt side - of a relationship of some form between the bank Deka, which knows the customers of the Sparkasse from their investment funds, and the WestLB.
Deta-Bank chief Franz Waas said at the presentation of the half-year figures at the end of August that he did not see any sense in the merger of the Mainzer Landstrasse house with a Land bank, either Helaba or WestLB.
However, the Board of Directors of the Deka, each half of which is supported by the banks of the Länder and the savings bank groups, instructed the Steering Committee to conduct negotiations with the WestLB with a view to joint commercial activities.
It could then be the flow of the financial market, or parts of it.
The talks, however, have only just begun, it is said in the Financial Place.
This is not the first time that Deta-Bank, which with its 3,000 employees counts as one of the most important employers on the Frankfurt financial market, has come into play when it comes to consolidating the savings banks sector.
In 2003, it was believed for a while that Deta-Bank could merge with the Rhineland-Palatinate bank and Halbab.
However, nothing has emerged from this ternary bouquet.
As soon as the plans had been made public, the Government of the Land of Hesse opposed Hellaba's participation in them.
After that, the other two houses did not join either.
The bank of the Land of Rhineland-Palatinate was instead attached to the bank of the Land of Baden-Wuttenberg in Stuttgart.
But there have always been new negotiations on the merger of the Deka-Bank with banks from Länder.
Finally, Günther Merl, chairman of the Hellaba board, had, however, opposed any commercial merger strategy with his bank.
Despite this, the feeling seems to be spreading that the grouping of the various public sector institutions is particularly urgent.
Now that the election to the Bavarian Land Parliament has passed, a union of the BayernLB with the Baden-Wuttenberg Land bank could become a reality first.
For Helaba, this is not particularly good news.
If the pressure that forces new mergers was to increase, the potential partners are gradually escaping it.
In the South, it would now be a junior partner, although it had hitherto better withstood the crisis than the banks of Munich and Stuttgart.
The Hesse-Thuringia savings and transfer group, which owns 85 percent of Helaba's capital, on the other hand, pulled a lock at the beginning of the year on any union with WestLB.
The NordLB would remain in place.
However, such geo-strategic reflections reflect only one facet.
Another aspect raises the question of how the different business models of each of these banks can match.
In June, Merl stated that the decisive question, which business model should ensure the future capacity of the Landesbanks, had not yet been resolved by the German savings and transfer grouping.
In the long run, a decommissioning of the WestLb could take place, decommissioning which is obviously not desired here.
This is also what is referred to in the letter of the incumbent Steering Committee: in any case, a <0x60>global solution' would be targeted for the establishment.
How all this will be put into the same basket with the union of some entities with the Deta-Bank remains to be seen.
