Insomnia Nights for Hypo Real Estate Shareholders
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted just a few weeks ago.
What a chance that the politician used the word “relatively” and slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared by the crisis movements.
This was indeed the case this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), on the side of the DAX, obtains from a consortium of German banks a credit of one billion to protect itself from the turbulence of the markets.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that aid credits are being issued up to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>35 billion.
Hypo Real Estate should now pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
The money comes from private banks as much as from public-law banks.
In the background, it is the Depfa subsidiary that bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself very short-term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible due to the mistrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank’s liquidity reserve had been reduced from 95 percent to 2.37 million euros, while the equity rate had also weakened slightly from 1.6 to 1.45 percent.
On-going and net profits from financial transactions fell to zero over the same period last year, with profits from the allocation of determined debts and securities and the termination of provisions in credit operations falling by more than 70 per cent to EUR 5 million.
And it was only thanks to the significant profits derived from the reimbursement of downstream accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as the reimbursement of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for the companies of the Konzern that the deficit of the gains was reduced by about 16 per cent.
After its privatization in 1990, the former state financier had first mis-speculated on industrial real estate loans, which had then been affiliated to Aareal Bank.
Because conventional state funding was not profitable enough, Depfa then engaged more intensively in infrastructure projects and in the financing of joint private-public-partnership (PPP) projects and diversified internationally.
On the value of the subsidiary, Hypo Real Estate must make amortizations that should have an essential material effect on the calculation of the group's gains and losses, which still remains rather vague.
The fact is that the dividends have been amputated.
By 2007, they had been cut to two-thirds.
Since the acquisition of Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has been a very important state and infrastructure investor.
It is more robust than other refinancing-dependent institutions in the inter-bank market as it has no customer deposits.
With the bankruptcy of the investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, lending between banks has again been considerably slow, with banks accumulating their liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs a short-term means of refinancing for some of Depfa's total credits - around <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>50 billion - annually.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group’s financing need is covered with medium-term credit and the company is protected from the influence of the largely out-of-state international financial markets at the moment.
Other sources say that refinancing would be secured through the funds until the end of 2009.
HRE Chairman Georg Funke, on the other hand, explained that the Hypo Real Estate group should no longer have to resort to financial markets in the medium term.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Financial Services Surveillance Establishment (Bafin) assume that the Hypo Real Group’s market capacity is now secured.
The bank’s shareholders and creditors have nothing but to hope for.
However, given the dynamics and imbalances of the crisis, there is no certainty.
Moreover, it is not unthinkable that funding should not be used in its entirety.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the fact that the bank is, according to the latest announcements, still on the doorstep of insolvency Sunday at the end of the evening, this rescue at least provisional will not succeed in reassuring the spirits either.
The share price collapsed from 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, perform particularly well.
While debt in the first place has barely moved, the prices of second-hand loans are declining.
The most affected are, of course, the investment funds of the former Württemberg Hypo subsidiary and those with a lifespan beyond 2009.
The bonds of the Hypo Real Estate bank seemed to be an alternative speculation investment, now their value must be considered dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the institution itself that brought the crisis into the institution by the purchase of the Depfa bank.
As long as issuing institutions, governments and less-affected commercial banks are still willing to support the system, it can be assumed that the backlog will be resorbed over time.
Or else it will happen what no one dares to expect right now - that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of renewed noises of partial nationalization, the probability approaching security has now become a mere well-founded hope.
This should primarily reserve insomnia nights for long-term creditors on deciding whether to separate from their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they drew a line on to constitute a loss deferral for the next few years on the next automatically levied capital gains tax.
