The rats also have feelings.
A rat or a cockroach flees from danger, does that mean he feels fear too?
The neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he experiences the same thing when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without which I or anyone else has so far been able to prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, one can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or in general consciousness, we enter difficult-to-practice terrain because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, flees or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our experience subjective to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits associated almost always with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its participation in short-term memory and in the directional and executional functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
At least so for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being differs even from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity might lie in the linguistic nature of Man: much of his existence being linked to language, it often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness should not depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, whatever the way it is produced, would probably differ a lot from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured or, due to this particular Hardware, analyzed based on our own experience, then its observation poses us with great problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is next to it another aspect of consciousness that should be more readily accessible scientifically.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined without taking into account their content, and this is exactly what happened in studies on the short-term memory of primates, particularly with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nervous correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: the two can be identical or not.
Curiously, this approach also emphasizes the weight of the prefrontal cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what does it mean for the emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
What we call “fear” is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the localized defense system in the brain (or its aftermath, like the reactions of the body) takes over from the vivid memory.
Thus observed, emotions are closely related to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our volatile nature, arise because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to impute them to others than to ourselves.
On the contrary, Antonio Damasio, for example, thinks that sensations from primitive activities are born in the regions of the cortex and brainstem body sensation, just like Jaak Pankseep who, however, focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could have been fully involved in transversal sensations of all kinds.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe this is undemonstrable.
Pankseep argues that what appears as fear in humans and rats is probably also felt as such in both cases: however, how could one check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach runs away from danger, but what if he feels fear?
In my opinion, similar behaviors are not enough to prove identical experiences.
True, the nervous comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brainstems, while cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brainstem at the origin of the sensations?
And even if we could prove it for Man, how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably completely different from ours (since human consciousness relies on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, there is progress on the nervous plane, as the same thing is measured in rats and in humans.
Since I do not explore language and consciousness in rats, nor sensations, I do not know if they exist.
We could judge this as short-term, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly hit a wall.
I am an emotional pragmatist.
