Dark matter influences the flight of space probes
For years, a mysterious phenomenon has left researchers puzzled: dark matter influences the speed of space probes during gravitational support maneuvers.
Experts fear that the general theory of relativity is not completely correct.
For almost 18 years, the space probe "Ulysses" has been flying in space.
Due to soon-frozen fuel pipelines, death threatens it.
For years, a mysterious phenomenon has been causing confusion among researchers - the anomaly of gravitational support.
Gravitational support is a maneuver of space probes, by which they obtain an additional momentum in the gravitational field of a celestial body, for example Earth.
Thus, the probes can save a lot of fuel.
The American-European research probe Cassini-Huygens used this physical trick, as did the solar probe Ulysses.
This is what has surprised researchers for years: flying objects do not always behave 100 percent the way they are expected to according to the venerable laws of gravity.
Moreover, irregularities appear at the speed level.
The probes unexpectedly become faster or slower.
Until now, physicists could not explain this effect.
They called it the anomaly of gravitational support.
Some experts feared that Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity, which describes the force of attraction of matter due to the curvature of space, might not be entirely correct.
The American physicist Stephen Adler of the Princeton Institute for Advanced Study still firmly believes that Einstein was not mistaken and tries to explain the anomaly of gravitational support using what is called the black matter that astronomers have identified in the universe.
"Black matter could be responsible for this anomaly, which is also close to Earth," he writes.
Space researchers have only known about the existence of dark matter for about ten years.
It apparently emanates from it a force of attraction whose effect is observable on other celestial bodies.
It, on the other hand, is completely invisible, that is, it does not emit or reflect any electromagnetic radiation, especially no visible light.
According to the calculations of scientists, black matter would still represent a good fifth of the entire mass of the universe.
