The German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of a few stages with singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer takes up the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Month of Flemish Photography, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, bigger every day," explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists able to convey on stage passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the audience.
To capture moments of personality of these artists, you do not need to take photos on stage.
They have a personality and a character of their own.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera the personality moments of the flamenco stars.”
With the festival "Song of the Mines", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about the dance or the song itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the audience with his art.
The search for the essentials and magic has been the constant of this work that we present these days at the El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata gallery.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographed artists.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book collection of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer’s passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the “Portraits of old sportsmen” (“SportARTproject”).
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, know them and be able to enter their lives for a moment or less long.
In photography, portraiture is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that sometimes you don’t know or that only give you a few minutes to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true.”
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is on display at the Galerie El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata, located at the number 20 of the Rue de la Mata (street parallel to the Hercules People's Square), which will be open until October 16th.
