Recidivists of alcohol at the wheel will have to install the 'alcolock' system
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative penalties for alcoholism to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the vehicle from starting intoxicated, or if it does not breathe.
The initiative was already announced last June and it now appears in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project that will last one year.
Its purpose is to reintegrate the driver by offering him road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State in charge of road safety as well as the Directorate-General for Road Safety and the Foundation Institute of Technology for Automotive Safety will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for driving more than once in a drunken state, resume the car.
Alcolock would avoid this since it is a connected system on the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not breathe before; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than authorized.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is at the expense of the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced offences by up to 65% in the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save the lives of 115 people each year.
This measure is based on administrative sanctions for two reasons: dealing with these behaviors before they become criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since the legal reform can be done by ordinary means but, however, the reform done by criminal means requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have an experimental one.
It is precisely tomorrow that the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative by the Spanish Socialist Party that proposes to install this system in school buses as it has been done in France.
