The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And most importantly, it regained public confidence that had been seriously shaken by the blood-contaminated scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from happening again.
As Judge Krever was late in filing his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Decary.
The situation was discouraging.
As a result of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field in the years that followed, we have regained public confidence," she said, before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Decary, however, keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were observed in Europe, says the one that has held the fort since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when this is not known and a serious disease can result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration leading inevitably to death, excution measures were introduced.
In April 1999, people who had stayed in the UK for more than a month since 1980 were denied blood.
Now, a few years ago, it has been demonstrated without a doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV screening technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests that allow the detection of the presence of the virus itself in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
The NATs have shortened the silent period, which extends between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors may become infected without knowing it and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years for a case of HIV transmission by a blood product to occur.
I believe that we can now feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," says the chief executive of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We need to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Decary before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
“Needs are increasing because the population is aging.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a boost in red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors, which on average comprises only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation.
However, anyone in good health who is 18 years of age or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is spreading, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With these 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this network of donors as they get older and can no longer give their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today’s life is so frantic, we rarely find time to spend an hour giving blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cordon blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample a few weeks ago and we plan to take more than a thousand a year.
We should start offering them for transplants early next year," says Dr. Decary, who describes this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed not to be able to access it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
