Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has filed a defamation lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small publishing house without the money in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of defamation lawsuits, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
For, for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of Black Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defenders in order to impose an amicable settlement that will rattle the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to look at the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was to public opinion that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally held through an exchange of ideas and not through a slash.
So it was enough for the mine to open its books, its records and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and dismisses the petitions and letters of support to the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both ask for a "public" debate while contemptuous of the opinions of that same public?
In the world of the Vice-President, it seems that this word only refers to heavily paid lawyers and not all Canadians; that is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public that supports Black Canada's authors and publishers does it primarily because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not within the framework of what many perceive as a stalker prosecution (following the "public debate", Barrick Gold has, moreover, just filed a warning to the authors of Black Canada's use of this...
Beyond Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, the pursuit of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in block, the right to the citation of credible sources and to the debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that displease the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under penalty of repeated prosecutions, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive prosecution clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for academia, as it is for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic bailout plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months still needs to be endorsed by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it provides for better monitoring by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right to look at the salaries paid to the leaders of the rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Representative to the negotiating table Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday, following a two-day negotiation marathon.
“We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets,” said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
“Everything has been done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
"That's the fundamental point: if we don't do that, the trauma, chaos and disruptions on Americans' daily lives will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had turned sprinting in the last few hours out of fear of the effect a new failure would have on investor sentiment.
The time limit we had agreed on was the opening of the markets this morning.
Associated late in the negotiations, the two candidates in the US presidential election were rather supportive of the agreement, but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction that one is forced to reach this extreme.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama attributed the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including the one to allow homeowners to keep their homes and the one on the salary of executives of companies rescued by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary,” he said on American television.
Asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
“The broad lines I’ve read [show] that it’s something we’re all going to have to digest and with which we’re going to be able to move forward.
The option to do nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to repurchase with taxpayers’ money the dubious, risky, and unsellable claims of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that initially led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and leading to a freeze in liquidity and bank failures.
It was a group of elected Republicans that overturned the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed that we have come out of this impasse since the Democrats have accepted that certain “toxic” assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round the corner for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to take losses for five years with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover its payout.
The new plan foresees the payment of a first tranche of 250 billion, which can be added to 100 billion if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion is expected to be endorsed by another vote of Congress.
In exchange for its help, Washington will obtain stakes in the companies it rescues that will be worth dividends in case of profit and that it will be able to resell when the turmoil is over.
The federal government will have the option of delaying seizure procedures for housing attached to the real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as setting limits on the remuneration and severance payments paid to the executives of the affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see it put to the vote in the House of Representatives today, and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Votes continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
“Obviously, Washington does not hear you,” Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But it is not about taking advantage of taxpayers.”
An animator of a small group in Congress dubbed "the skeptics' caucus", Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred distinguished economics professors, including three Nobel Prize laureates, have written to us to tell us: Congress is being asked not to rush and to carefully examine the way forward," he said.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the banking group Fortis for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was renouncing the acquisition of its competitor in full wreck since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US dollars) in the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the top 20 European banks and the top ten insurers.
"This is not money lost," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, one regains a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It’s just something that savers and households appreciate now that times are uncertain.”
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed on the verge of nationalizing another bank battered by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take back all the loans underway at Bradford and Bringley Bank, including more than 41 billion (75.5 billion US dollars) in real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
