The psychology of over-tendering: why do we spend more money?
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Researchers in neurology and economics at the University of New York have succeeded in updating the neurological and economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, humans don’t want to be distanced in this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that’s why they even prefer to pay a price too high.
This research has attempted to draw up a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group participated in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain areas of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the over-tendering of a third, the whole under the brainstem, called the striatum, moved intensively during the loss of the game.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight in front of the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economist members of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
In these cases, three groups over-tendered against a partner, in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and so they carried out their placement.
