Hepatitis: when should we consult a doctor?
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that there are 100 miles of patients with the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only 7 miles are treated, often because the patients do not know that they are the carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to the pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travelers, it is recommended to get vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated foods, usually accompanied by a bad general condition, weakness, stomach aches and nausea.
Then a visible jaundice develops on the skin and on the white of the eye, the stools become lighter and the urine takes on a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, one million people die each year from the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are not aware of the virus, because the pathogenic gene sneakily destroys the cells of the liver. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattooed people.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine examination in the laboratory, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as you notice symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its goal is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Do those who believe in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would work as a sort of analgesic, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British newspaper Telegraph published an article according to which researchers from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment by analyzing at what level belief in God could influence the tolerance of the human being to pain.
As part of this at least bizarre experience, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Through a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for the regulation of pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments, in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
Specifically, the experiment takes place in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and scattering electroshocks is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at two paintings in a sustained way, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the Hermione painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experiment hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary evokes a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, concerned its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time, received 20 electroshocks in four successive parts, while watching either the religious-themed painting or the more general-themed painting.
The Catholics said that in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt “safe,” like someone they were “care for” and they “calmed down, and peace invaded them.”
In view of the religious-themed painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they were watching Leonardo's work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in atheists, provided that the appropriate photo is found.
"We should find an image to which they react very positively, such as a mother or father," the psychologist said.
