The smart car mimics the theft of the buzzer
What better method would it be to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if not the imitation of an obstacle detector already existing in nature?
Like, for example, the bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, held in Japan, the buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic starting point, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-driving robotic control system, type BR23C, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval in shape, which in reality is very similar to our safe protective shell - explained, at the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development and public relations technology department of the brand.
The faceted eye of the bee plays a primary role, as it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which transforms it into an immediate avoidance maneuver.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from a sufficient angle to avoid collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoidance maneuver is entirely instinctive.
“If it weren’t for this, the mini car robot wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle,” says Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid the other bees.
The process must take place in a blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, only the rotary movement, acceleration and slowdown could be used as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and whose energy concentrate is larger, which makes their lifespan longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not data processing, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism should only process a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store and react with the intuitive logic based on the data of previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
You don't need a memory of a capacity of gigabytes, or even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards designing a technology for instant avoidance, and according to Nissan estimates, this system will make its way into mass-produced cars over the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles in his way.
