Industrial prices have continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - reports the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to a year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of domestic and export price fluctuations, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices rose only to a lesser extent: by 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors only experienced a slight increase of around 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather goods and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 percent), with firstly, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 percent, then the production of shoes with a monthly increase of 2.5 percent.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical products and materials manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
This led to deflation in the oil processing (1.4 per cent), electrical machinery and appliances (0.9 per cent) and a slight increase in the wood processing (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry recorded an increase of between 0.2 percent and 0.9 percent.
In the sectors of supply of electricity, gas, steam and water, representing a significant weight in the national industrial operation, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the price of gas put in place by the authorities since July 1.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, the prices of the oil processing sector experienced the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the major food, beverage and tobacco production sector, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price decreases have occurred in the textile and textile products (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacturing of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 percent to 9.1 percent.
In the processing industry as a whole, prices rose by 10.2 percent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent from the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to the allocation of sectors, in August, it was the initiating sectors of profit-on-investment that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 percent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices rose by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and materials production sectors for further processing did not change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while for the profit-making sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent.
The export prices of the industrial sector, in HUF, increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
