Mp3 player pointed with the finger, they put at risk the hearing.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players, can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a statement issued in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee on unforeseen and recently identified health risks of the EU (Csserri), published today.
According to this scientific report, 5-10% of those who listen to music at full volume over a period of at least 5 years using portable music devices, for more than an hour a day and a week, are at risk of permanent loss of hearing capacity.
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and full-volume mobile phones may unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably," Kuneva said.
"According to the scientific data, this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We also need to re-examine existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increasing number of young people exposed to noise they generate.
"Scientists-concluded the EU executive-confirm that there are good reasons to be concerned, and that the European Commission will now discuss with Member States and other interested parties, what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents, against similar exposure to noise from musical devices and portable devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit this data by using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the current limits on the maximum noise level in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods of time are at risk of permanent loss of hearing ability after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to around 2.5 and 10 million people in the U.S.
Rome, Alemanno gave the order to send the Commission for the future of the capital.
Today we start, in March we finish, in June we will draw the sums.
This is the calendar set by the Capitol for the work of the "Commission for the Future of Rome Capital", which took place this morning, at the new headquarters, behind the Baths of Caracalla.
In six months' time, President Antonio Marzano and the other 49 Commission members will develop the directives for Rome.
In March, when they are finished, the Committee and the Municipal Council will evaluate the analyses and projects, in order to present in June the Strategic Plan for Rome with the "official stamp" of the Capitol and its mayor Gianni Alemanno.
"The Commission is absolutely independent; all political, social and cultural ideas are represented in it," Alemanno said, "it will have to propose ideas for the development of Rome, which will be used by the political decision-makers, who remain the Committee and the Municipal Council.
No overlapping of roles, but only the desire to have a corner where to develop a great project for Rome.
In March, it will finish its tasks and then disappear, because this experience must have a precise time duration.
In June-announced the mayor- we will present the strategic plan resulting from the work carried out by the Commission for the future of Rome Capital. "
For those who accuse the Commission of being useless, since its opinions will not be binding, Alemanno replies: "It all depends on the work that the Commission will be able to do, as well as the quality of its proposals.
If the quality is there, as in France thanks to the Attali Commission, as in Rome, I am sure, its contribution will be fundamental.
Too often politics is burdened by day-to-day management and emergencies that occur from time to time.
We, on the contrary, want to look forward, and further, to a deeper perspective, seriously working on the development of Rome and its future."
In addition, the mayor of Rome wishes to emphasize that "this Commission is not a useless body or a bureaucratic whole: it is absolutely free, and will not cost a euro to the Roman citizens, and will serve to study and participate the best intelligences that express the Capital.
For Alemanno, in fact, "it takes a draft strategic reference, neither firm nor immobile, in order to allow our city to improve, which it absolutely needs, while thinking about its future now a unitary spirit, ".
A future that will not be limited to the usual communal borders, but that will look further, not only from the perspective of the future metropolitan city and its legal status as Capital, but also in relation to the role that Rome can and must have, as the Capital of Europe and the Mediterranean.
