The elites are in danger.
The phenomenon had already manifested a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the $700 billion bailout plan approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday that confirms this by telling us that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its former East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions as well as to the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "the Washingtons" and to the world of finance in the South, especially powerful in the South.
The soul, in fact, which made itself felt despotically with the vote of which I spoke to you at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is just one example of the changes, of the great changes that the ongoing economic earthquake foretells or already lets run: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and maybe not only here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena covered for some time, to such an extent that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of sovereign state, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking and financial institutions that, of course, have close relations with foreign countries, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global, but politically, it is almost national.
Political internationalisation really seems out of the question, or does not have much to say: the obvious evidence is provided to us by the European Union, which, as usual, is divided between the various interests and between the various national strategies, and does not manage to decide on any common policy line.
And so, it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all an affection for credits: when you go through a difficult period, there are only those states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements that no international market or organization can ever have in a similar way.
This new emphasis on the nation-state crisis is, after all, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that the more recent economic developments of the economy tend to attach to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
. Paradoxically, in fact, when we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at once that our future will, on the contrary, have to pay more and more taxes.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth, but that are absolutely related to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more cards than he who is not, that is, he who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, provides for a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take control of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proven inadequate and full of shadow zone.
And moreover, something even deeper, in a sense, even troubling: a discredit, a suffering, a picture of inadequacy, a feeling of distance that tends to involve the entire class of directors in an increasing number of Western countries.
