The super glue to walk on the walls.
Defeat the laws of gravity with a super glue and, in the future, walk on the walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centers, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring just 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers managed to keep a 100 kilogram body glued to a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know that use a particular structure of carbon, called nano carbon tubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists took inspiration from the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that ensure the animal, a perfect adherent.
Tests carried out on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it “easily detaches from the wall,” explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton’s Faculty of Engineering.
MARKING ON THE WALLS? –" this material could be used as a temporary adhesive" adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on the walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could relate to aerospace engineering.
For now, no superheroes.
THE OTHER RESEARCH- The University of Berkeley, California, is also looking for a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, California researchers presented a microfiber-like hair adhesive that cleans itself of dust during movement on a surface to ensure perfect and consistent adhesion.
Medications: never with fruit juices.
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed especially in the summer, because they are soothing and rich in vitamins, if combined with certain vital drugs, alter their absorption, increasing or decreasing, depending on the case, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, reminds them of the risks of fruit juices, whether in cans or fresh, if associated with the intake of certain drugs; during the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he is launching a new alarm for patients, suffices for them to get rid of them.
Grapefruit juice has already been heavily criticized for being held responsible for increasing the effects of certain anti-arrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, anti-stem and neurological drugs to toxic levels.
It was the Italian Medicines Agency itself, which had given the news in a two-year news bulletin, warning doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger derived from this mix and to pay attention to what one is drinking, if one is taking medicines such as, for example, Diazepam or Méthado.
According to experts, even the orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit the drugs.
Long is the list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
Michele Carruba, director of the Department of Pharmacology at the Public University of Milan, said: "These findings are generally immediately reported to the various national and international drug agencies who will have to change the information notes of the drugs if necessary.
It is always necessary to read the illustrative papers of the medicines you are taking, and, if something is not clear, not to be impressed, but to speak clearly to the doctor or pharmacist," the expert pointed out to the agency Ansa.
The Nobel Prize in Economics for Paul Krugman.
The Nobel Prize in Economics was awarded to the American Paul Krugman for his research on business models and the location of economic activities.
Krugman, 55, is a New Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and he is also a noted New York Times editorialist.
Krugman is one of the Bush administration’s biggest critics of foreign policy and economic solutions.
A few months after the September 2001 attacks, during the days of Enron's bankruptcy, Krugman had written, in an article published in the New York Times, that the second event would have been more decisive than the first, in terms of consequences on U.S. history.
A forecast that unleashed many controversies, and which was reproached to the economist for years, but which has now turned out to be accurate.
“I’m surprised and even a little shocked by the speed with which the memory of scandals such as the collapse of Enron or Worldcom have disappeared from the public’s attention,” Krugman said at the end of 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi, of the European Central Bank’s executive committee, Krugman is a “high-value economist” but also a very aggressive publicist, particularly critical of the Bush administration’s excesses of liberalism.
