Students victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student housing market is not in crisis
According to the latest survey by the Sunia, the tenants' union, renting a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people, the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families from origin have to support," explains the head of the study office of Sunia, Laura Mariani.
In most cases, the rental offers also involve a series of violations: free type contracts, not registered, no rent limit, sub-leases.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of the tax, are necessary to calm the prices.
Reading the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, we go from 650 euros minimum (zone Bande Nere), to an average value of 800 (zone Lambiate, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (zone Vittoria)
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and from 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), we ask about 600 euros for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euros for a single) for areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>).
You can only save if you move away in the peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed, and 450 for a single in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a single one, we spend from 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari, for a bed, you have to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single one.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the urban economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rentals are often taken by extra-community students, have a further anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, the cities feed the historic rooms.
The historic cinemas close in favor of the Multiplex.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centers, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multi-rooms, and the death of consumption of mono-rooms in central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems to us inevitable and undeniable; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, these are often historical places and loaded with memory, "it's as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of a path and so many emotions" observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the Grand Prix of the Oscar as well
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of merchants, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 cinemas of the traditional type have closed, and it is the halls of the main cities that have mostly paid the cost: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, the Roman Emilia leads with 82 cinemas mono rooms lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and in Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed in an irrational way," observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but we should still guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room is closed in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the failed deliberation of credit in favour of traders: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>16 and <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>18 million per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, decided to solve the situation thanks to the signing of a protocol between the City Hall and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote mono-room cinemas in the historical centers and on the outskirts.
Among the proposed regulations, there are tax incentives for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted area, and will have special rates for parking and in some car parks.
"This is an initiative that I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna in implementing other measures.
However, it is obvious that, to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema de Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" that I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so much of shared emotions, I turn to the other side to not see the panels blackened by dust.
