When energy is born from waves, now the big ones are launched.
It’s an oversized deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and now the world’s largest energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources that giants like Chevron have looked at, and are now trying to get their hands on.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for hundreds of years now, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil give a great boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world’s electricity demand could be covered by offshore swell operating systems.
That is twice as much as nuclear power plants produce.
And in addition, there would be currents and tides..
Colossus in attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build an installation in the north of Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a truly revolutionary step.
Two years after that, more and more candidates among these companies dedicated to traditional energy are betting on marine energy.
“Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies,” said a spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant, in the Wall Street Journal, “and it is assessing opportunities to cooperate with us.”
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a deliberate permit by the U.S. Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially considering that in Alaska, the United States continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush set up a project for new excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which are traversing the path of energy coming from the sea, and the amounts invested to date, although their details are not known, according to observers, a growing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology still in its infancy, apart from the fact that marine energy does not dispel fears of environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in size, and do not seem to be causing major problems to the ecosystem.
In order to produce energy on a large scale, however, it is necessary to use technologies with a higher environmental impact.
And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the sludge up and down, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure drives a turbine which in turn feeds a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through submarine cables.
At the moment, we have four systems of this kind in the project phase, pending a single federal approval and part of the energy could be used for a military facility.
Green Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping mall and parking lot using six marine turbines on New York’s East River.
The movement of water during tides rotates the blades of the turbines, creating a rotating movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant has announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to extract energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they tell the Institute for Electric Energy Research, deserves at this time, the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable from wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it is on the energy of the tides that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others, look to the coasts, invested $7 and a half million in 2008, and foresees investments up to $35 million in 2009.
